description: Data, facts or figures about an individual; the set of relevant items would depend on the use case
A unique proper name or character sequence that identifies this individual
Additional identifiers that identify an individual
A categorical value that groups this individual by age (e.g., "Adult", "18-24 years", etc.)
The year on which this individual was born
The month on which this individual was born
The calendar date on which this individual was born

Assigned gender is this individual's gender which was assigned at birth, typically by a medical and/or legal organization, and then later registered with other organizations. Such a designation is typically based off of the superficial appearance of external genitalia present at birth.

This individual's concept of self as being male and masculine or female and feminine, or ambivalent, based in part on physical characteristics, parental responses, and psychological and social pressures. It is the internal experience of gender role. For practical reasons the lookups are limited to first and second-level entries, but can be expanded when needed. Note that 'Gender at birth', 'Genotypic sex' and any (gender-related) hormone therapies in 'Medication' are usually medically more relevant than this term.
The gender of this individual used for administrative purposes
A biological sex quality inhering in an individual based upon genotypic composition of sex chromosomes
The country that this individual was born in
The country that this individual reported as residing in at the time of enrollment
An individual's descent or lineage, from another individual or from a population using ancestry informative markers (AIMs) based on genetic/genomic data
A reference to an event (sequencing run, sample preparation, etc.) relating to this individual
A reference to materials (files, samples etc) relating to this individual

Consent given by a patient to a surgical or medical procedure or participation in a study, examination or analysis after achieving an understanding of the relevant medical facts and the risks involved.
The status of an individual in relationship to participation in a given activty
The age at which death occurred
One or more associations between the individual and an organisation.
Information related to this individual that is not captured by this system, but is available or provided by one or more organisations.
One or more biosamples associated with an individual
Reference to one or more results that were produced from detailed examination of data derived from this individual
A record of descent or ancestry, particularly of a specific condition or trait, indicating individual family members, their relationships, and their status with respect to the trait or condition.
A reference to one or more resources that organises records in a meaningful way (e.g., data releases, subpopulations, cohorts, etc.)
The source or origin of the record. For example, an organisation, database, system, etc.
The date the record was created at the source
The person who created the record at the source
The date the record was updated at the source
The person who updated the record at the source
A written explanation, observation or criticism added to textual material.
